1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:25,800
 It just seems to me like there is probably some MBA things that need to be said here,

2
00:00:25,800 --> 00:00:29,480
 given the text exchanges the last day or so.

3
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:34,180
 We did quite a bit of texting on it, so let's air some of that out.

4
00:00:34,500 --> 00:00:35,940
 Sorry about your pacers, buddy.

5
00:00:36,560 --> 00:00:38,140
 I don't need to talk about it. It's fine.

6
00:00:39,820 --> 00:00:42,640
 Hey, sorry TJ Warren got shut the fuck down.

7
00:00:42,940 --> 00:00:46,460
 TJ Warren. What a second half that guy had, huh?

8
00:00:47,580 --> 00:00:49,040
 Yeah. Yeah.

9
00:00:49,440 --> 00:00:52,800
 This bubble gameplay has been so surprisingly good.

10
00:00:53,400 --> 00:00:53,800
 I agree.

11
00:00:54,280 --> 00:00:55,620
 It's been great to watch.

12
00:00:56,520 --> 00:01:01,320
 I agree, and the number of really good, I mean, well-played games and then good finishes,

13
00:01:01,860 --> 00:01:07,460
 you know, like the close games versus blowout quotient is way better than the normal season.

14
00:01:08,020 --> 00:01:11,320
 You know, it seems to me, and it may just be because of the compression time,

15
00:01:11,380 --> 00:01:17,180
 because these guys, I mean, I think that they live 24-7 basketball during this time of the season anyway,

16
00:01:17,180 --> 00:01:20,180
 but, like, this is especially just...

17
00:01:21,040 --> 00:01:21,880
 What else are you going to do?

18
00:01:22,820 --> 00:01:24,260
 We'll get a lot of haircuts.

19
00:01:25,340 --> 00:01:31,700
 I mean, maybe the pressure of the pandemic is, like, focusing all of them in some implicit way as well, you know?

20
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:34,340
 I mean, they're going out, they're playing hard.

21
00:01:34,700 --> 00:01:37,480
 Like, these are good games, so...

22
00:01:37,480 --> 00:01:46,940
 This is also where the social justice directive that the league has taken up, I think, has made it...

23
00:01:46,940 --> 00:01:52,180
 No, I feel like players feel like they're playing for more than just basketball, too, which makes a difference.

24
00:01:52,640 --> 00:01:53,980
 Yeah. They respect the commissioner.

25
00:01:54,280 --> 00:01:56,480
 They probably respect most of the coaches.

26
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:00,720
 Like, yeah, it's like a good relationship that they all have with each other, unlike the NFL.

27
00:02:00,920 --> 00:02:05,700
 I was just going to say, like, who could imagine a league like that?

28
00:02:05,960 --> 00:02:10,640
 I noticed that last night after the Lakers game in LeBron's postgame.

29
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:18,460
 You could tell his response to the questions were about the historical moment, not about the game, right?

30
00:02:18,540 --> 00:02:21,280
 It was like, it's good for us to go out in a time like this.

31
00:02:21,340 --> 00:02:25,000
 In other words, like, he sees his role, and I don't think he's alone in this,

32
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,140
 but, I mean, he sees his role in a postgame interview as not being a representative of the Lakers primarily,

33
00:02:31,320 --> 00:02:34,460
 but as being a sort of spokesperson for social justice.

34
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:36,500
 He's done that from the beginning of the bubble.

35
00:02:36,700 --> 00:02:40,300
 It's like he, you know, in the first couple interviews, he was asked questions about the games,

36
00:02:40,440 --> 00:02:44,620
 and then he completely ignored them, and was talking about justice for Breonna Taylor, right?

37
00:02:44,840 --> 00:02:46,080
 Right, right, right.

38
00:02:46,560 --> 00:02:51,040
 That's definitely cool, but I feel like, at least for me, if I was exhausted after a game,

39
00:02:51,040 --> 00:02:54,020
 I'd be like, shit, what are my talking points about racism?

40
00:02:54,860 --> 00:02:57,720
 I forgot my good, like, points I had in my head.

41
00:02:58,280 --> 00:02:58,860
 I know.

42
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:02,780
 I mean, they don't, they don't, we don't think about that very often.

43
00:03:02,860 --> 00:03:05,720
 The postgame interview, it's like, just think of it, I mean,

44
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:08,520
 I obviously never played anywhere near a level like that,

45
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:11,640
 but the times after I had, like, a hard couple of hours of basketball,

46
00:03:11,800 --> 00:03:15,080
 it's like, ask me a question, I'd be like, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

47
00:03:15,080 --> 00:03:17,420
 I don't have anything going on to say.

48
00:03:17,780 --> 00:03:18,900
 Racism is bad.

49
00:03:19,260 --> 00:03:20,260
 Racism sucks.

50
00:03:20,680 --> 00:03:21,000
 Yeah.

51
00:03:21,540 --> 00:03:21,940
 Shit.

52
00:03:22,820 --> 00:03:23,520
 You know.

53
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:24,300
 Water.

54
00:03:24,440 --> 00:03:25,400
 That's impressive, man.

55
00:03:25,600 --> 00:03:25,920
 Yeah.

56
00:03:27,980 --> 00:03:30,000
 I mean, could you imagine Jordan doing that, though?

57
00:03:30,700 --> 00:03:31,220
 Yeah, well.

58
00:03:31,480 --> 00:03:35,040
 Well, he'd just be like, well, they all buy sneakers, or whatever his quote was.

59
00:03:35,400 --> 00:03:36,380
 Republicans buy sneakers.

60
00:03:36,560 --> 00:03:37,880
 Racists buy Jordans, too.

61
00:03:37,980 --> 00:03:40,000
 I mean, I'm not going to alienate them.

62
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:51,140
 I'm just, I mean, just the way that James has cultivated himself as a figure in and beyond sport is, I mean, it's just really impressive.

63
00:03:52,280 --> 00:04:04,180
 Well, that's what, I mean, I think I said that before, but that was one of the takeaways for me of the Jordan Bulls miniseries that, you know, was like, if there was a debate between LeBron and Jordan, I think there is no longer one.

64
00:04:04,180 --> 00:04:09,680
 Like, LeBron is a way better figure of, you know, just in all facets.

65
00:04:10,440 --> 00:04:10,780
 For sure.

66
00:04:10,780 --> 00:04:11,980
 He's like a decent human.

67
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:13,660
 Yeah.

68
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:15,060
 An actual role model.

69
00:04:15,500 --> 00:04:15,620
 Yeah.

70
00:04:15,660 --> 00:04:15,980
 Yes.

71
00:04:16,220 --> 00:04:16,740
 That's right.

72
00:04:17,080 --> 00:04:17,640
 That's right.

73
00:04:17,660 --> 00:04:18,560
 Now, let's just pray.

74
00:04:18,560 --> 00:04:20,260
 Not a sociopath.

75
00:04:20,740 --> 00:04:22,860
 Let's pray that LeBron doesn't have any skeletons.

76
00:04:23,300 --> 00:04:24,480
 You know, that would be the worst.

77
00:04:24,560 --> 00:04:26,780
 He gets canceled somewhere in the next couple years.

78
00:04:26,940 --> 00:04:27,160
 God.

79
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:28,280
 I know.

80
00:04:28,520 --> 00:04:30,640
 That would, that would, that would.

81
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:32,400
 But, I mean, think of the pressure on him.

82
00:04:32,580 --> 00:04:35,000
 Because, do you remember, Nathaniel, I talked to you about this.

83
00:04:35,060 --> 00:04:35,520
 You remember this.

84
00:04:35,560 --> 00:04:42,000
 But remember after the China thing, I was like, I was down on Harden and LeBron because they were sort of apologists for the NBA and that.

85
00:04:42,460 --> 00:04:47,040
 And I can't remember who made the comment, but I thought it was a really great comment and it changed my mind on it.

86
00:04:47,040 --> 00:04:58,040
 Where they were like, you're asking this guy who's, you know, MVP, perennial MVP candidate of the NBA and does so much stuff to, like, know everything about every global political issue.

87
00:04:58,380 --> 00:05:00,180
 And this is just one that he doesn't know about.

88
00:05:00,700 --> 00:05:02,260
 And give him a fucking break.

89
00:05:02,320 --> 00:05:04,000
 And I was like, that's a really good point.

90
00:05:04,500 --> 00:05:13,480
 You know, I was like, yeah, I kind of am being a jerk by getting pissed at him for not taking a stand against, you know, humanitarian abuses in China.

91
00:05:13,700 --> 00:05:14,560
 Like, come on.

92
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:27,380
 It gives it that vibe of a giant, like, giant life-size appropriation machine.

93
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,240
 You know, it's just eating all difference.

94
00:05:31,740 --> 00:05:34,640
 I don't think you can discount that reading of Hegel either.

95
00:05:34,780 --> 00:05:40,960
 I mean, that is sort of more of the traditional reading, I think, like, as opposed to the people I've been dealing with.

96
00:05:41,480 --> 00:05:44,240
 But, you know, the totalizing impulse is there.

97
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:45,800
 It runs all throughout.

98
00:05:46,020 --> 00:05:52,060
 It's just, again, the way I've been reading it is that it's not that that totalizing impulse is, like, celebrated.

99
00:05:52,660 --> 00:05:55,080
 It's more that it's just, it's schematized, right?

100
00:05:55,080 --> 00:06:04,440
 So, the shift to absolute spirit is not, like, finding joy in this totalizing monster.

101
00:06:04,880 --> 00:06:18,420
 It's really just a recognition of that impulse and kind of, like, for me, at least, it functions as a warning about that impulse rather than, like, yay, go appropriation, you know?

102
00:06:19,220 --> 00:06:20,120
 Yeah, yeah.

103
00:06:21,580 --> 00:06:26,020
 Although, in all fairness, it is a, appropriation is a development.

104
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:26,680
 It's progressive.

105
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:28,080
 So, it is kind of a yay.

106
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:35,320
 I mean, it's not, like, I mean, he doesn't have to be a fan of it in order to see it as a progressive advancement.

107
00:06:36,520 --> 00:06:45,120
 And the need he feels, as many do and did, to distinguish his thing from other things.

108
00:06:45,120 --> 00:06:48,620
 I mean, that's a hugely important element of it, I think.

109
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:52,560
 And that's very related to what, to your diss project, right?

110
00:06:52,620 --> 00:07:05,380
 Like, that I think a key part of this now, not just a sort of ancillary part from which to begin, a key part of this is the need to have something that's distinct from the other thinkers before me.

111
00:07:05,880 --> 00:07:10,600
 It's part of what lends it that, like, well, not that stuff, you know?

112
00:07:10,700 --> 00:07:10,960
 Right.

113
00:07:11,140 --> 00:07:16,500
 Well, there's so many pressures that create that scholarly move, especially today.

114
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:17,300
 Sure, sure.

115
00:07:17,560 --> 00:07:19,480
 I mean, in Hegel's time, it was obviously strongly felt.

116
00:07:19,580 --> 00:07:21,900
 But today, I mean, that's the way you brand yourself.

117
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,740
 It's like, it's an unavoidable move to some extent.

118
00:07:24,740 --> 00:07:36,900
 And that's the thing that I find problematic in Barad, is that, you know, her whole idea is difference, an ontological difference, where basically it's grounded in this relationality.

119
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:48,540
 But she's so invested in making what I see as basically arbitrary cuts away from Butler and away from Foucault and away from deconstruction, even away from Niels Bohr, who's like her boy.

120
00:07:48,920 --> 00:07:51,240
 And it's like, why do you need to do that?

121
00:07:51,240 --> 00:08:05,180
 Yeah, that's the same vibe I had when I read, like, the Harmon and the object-oriented stuff, was I was just like, it just seemed so committed to a branding operation that I was just kind of, eh.

122
00:08:05,880 --> 00:08:06,980
 No, I mean, I get it.

123
00:08:07,140 --> 00:08:08,360
 Like, you have to do it.

124
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:10,760
 It's just how you do that, how you stylize that.

125
00:08:10,840 --> 00:08:11,920
 I don't agree with that, though.

126
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:19,160
 I mean, that to me, for me at least, that was the project of the last book and certainly will be for this one, is like, I don't think that you have to do it.

127
00:08:19,160 --> 00:08:31,180
 I mean, look, in all fairness, yes, you have, at some level, you're not making everything indistinct, but I also do think that you don't have to, for instance, one of the things that's crucial for me is I'm not going to invent new words.

128
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:38,760
 I'm not going to have an ambient rhetoric or I'm not going to have a new, like, there's no, there's no new terminology for me, right?

129
00:08:38,760 --> 00:08:53,760
 Like, and that's been an important one for me all along, is I don't want to, it's like, you know how everyone does that as a way of summarizing their thing, like, rhetoricity or, you know, what's Diane's, I can't even, was it rhetoricity?

130
00:08:54,040 --> 00:08:55,280
 It's rhetoricity, yeah, that's it.

131
00:08:55,420 --> 00:08:55,540
 Yeah, okay.

132
00:08:55,900 --> 00:09:13,700
 So, but again, like, each of those, those are attempts to sort of, like, slightly distinguish and for me it's always been like, no, I'm going to use the same terminology that everybody else uses so that there's nothing distinctive, you know, at that level that you can point to and say, well, Muckelbauer's theory of X, you know.

133
00:09:13,760 --> 00:09:17,060
 Right. It's easy to see why people, it's easy to see why people do it, though.

134
00:09:17,140 --> 00:09:17,480
 Of course.

135
00:09:17,540 --> 00:09:30,300
 I mean, it, it, it rubs me the wrong way, but, like, in terms of, like, the dynamics of the institution and the publishing industry, it's almost difficult not to at least attempt some of those moves because, I mean, look at Barad.

136
00:09:30,580 --> 00:09:35,300
 I mean, as annoying as all that stuff is, that's the reason why we're talking, that's why we're talking about her.

137
00:09:35,300 --> 00:09:36,420
 That's right, that's right.

138
00:09:36,720 --> 00:09:43,180
 But that's where, I mean, that's where, like, taking the, this is where the Deleuze becoming imperceptible is really interesting to me, is.

139
00:09:43,760 --> 00:09:47,680
 It's not a question of, it doesn't necessarily have to be.

140
00:09:48,020 --> 00:09:53,140
 So all of those sort of, what, because those pressures are kind of external pressures, right?

141
00:09:53,180 --> 00:09:55,000
 They're not the pressures from the thinking.

142
00:09:55,440 --> 00:09:56,820
 They're pressures from institutions.

143
00:09:57,120 --> 00:10:02,980
 They're pressures from, you know, all those, not pressures, but forces that induce that.

144
00:10:02,980 --> 00:10:07,400
 And there's, I mean, it doesn't seem to me that there's anything about the thinking that requires that.

145
00:10:07,860 --> 00:10:22,380
 There are things about an individual who writes, you know, in an institution in ecology that wants to get, again, recognition that requires a distinctiveness or a branding of some kind.

146
00:10:22,380 --> 00:10:41,180
 But I think there's a lot to be said for, and I, hopefully I'm going to try to say it, you know, for, like, for the indistinguishability, for the ambiguity, uncertainty, whatever terminology of, like, not knowing how my thing is different from, you know, everyone else's.

147
00:10:41,180 --> 00:10:48,860
 And really thinking that it's not, you know, other than that it's, like, my name's on the book and not someone else's name.

148
00:10:49,460 --> 00:10:51,800
 So, and even that's not necessary.

149
00:10:52,420 --> 00:10:58,660
 Now, I get that, but, like, most people, even some of the better thinkers are not that self-conscious.

150
00:10:59,400 --> 00:11:08,680
 Like, if, so, I would, I would, I don't know, I would challenge a little bit that idea of, like, the external pressure because it's completely internalized in Barad, right?

151
00:11:08,680 --> 00:11:13,640
 I mean, the, she's an effect of biopower rather than a commentator on it.

152
00:11:14,060 --> 00:11:14,620
 You know what I mean?

153
00:11:14,880 --> 00:11:15,120
 Yeah.

154
00:11:15,580 --> 00:11:15,820
 So.

155
00:11:16,440 --> 00:11:34,020
 Well, maybe I'm wrong to call it simply external, but I'm just saying it does seem to me imaginable, or at least I've tried that in my work of, like, pursuing, for me, the indistinguishability between my thinking and the thing that I'm reading, for instance, such that when you read it, you don't really know.

156
00:11:34,020 --> 00:11:36,240
 I mean, I learned that from Derrida to a certain extent.

157
00:11:36,660 --> 00:11:39,780
 But, look, Derrida's branded himself quite well, right?

158
00:11:39,940 --> 00:11:42,220
 Like, Difference and, you know.

159
00:11:43,460 --> 00:11:45,440
 So, I mean, I don't know.

160
00:11:45,660 --> 00:11:50,140
 Maybe it's going to turn out that I'm just, at the end of the day, I'm going to be wrong about this one.

161
00:11:50,320 --> 00:11:55,900
 But I think it's, as a project, it's, at least to me, a more interesting one of, like, I don't want it to be recognized.

162
00:11:56,280 --> 00:11:58,220
 Or, rather, it doesn't matter, maybe.

163
00:11:58,340 --> 00:11:59,660
 It's not that I don't want it to be.

164
00:11:59,900 --> 00:12:02,380
 But it doesn't matter, you know.

165
00:12:03,340 --> 00:12:13,380
 I mean, what I find tiresome about the constant branding is then you're, like, swimming in, I feel like I'm swimming in terms with a little R's and T's, you know, next to them.

166
00:12:13,620 --> 00:12:16,940
 That, you know, that they're hard to mobilize.

167
00:12:17,420 --> 00:12:24,580
 I, one of the difficulties I had writing early on was trying to mobilize these terms.

168
00:12:24,740 --> 00:12:34,880
 And because they were so specifically attached to specific teacher or to specific scholars that I felt like I had to be faithful to the thing that they were doing.

169
00:12:35,040 --> 00:12:38,580
 But the more generic concepts were just far more pliable.

170
00:12:39,900 --> 00:12:53,740
 And I do find something different with, like, I mean, a lot of the terms that Derrida, you know, that we consider to be Derridian are not positive concepts in that, like, they're Derrida's idea or concept of this thing.

171
00:12:53,740 --> 00:13:13,360
 But they're more, like, dynamics or structures or phenomenon that are undergoing that Derrida just thinks through, which, like, then becomes invitations for other people to think through as well without it being more or less faithful to Derrida's conception of the thing.

172
00:13:13,700 --> 00:13:22,880
 And, in fact, the one thing that Derrida resisted the most was turning something into deconstruction into a thing or a method or a process, like, whatever else it is.

173
00:13:22,880 --> 00:13:28,700
 Like, that – insofar as he branded himself, he was the – it's not a thing, branding, right?

174
00:13:28,800 --> 00:13:29,480
 It's not a product.

175
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:31,880
 But that's also – I mean –

176
00:13:31,880 --> 00:13:32,200
 Yes.

177
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:32,540
 Right?

178
00:13:32,600 --> 00:13:36,580
 Like, I mean, so, for instance, he didn't stop talking about deconstruction.

179
00:13:36,820 --> 00:13:39,080
 He talked endlessly about deconstruction.

180
00:13:39,140 --> 00:13:46,880
 Now, what he always said about deconstruction, not a word, not a concept, not – you know, like, he always – but it was – I mean, again, that's to me – I think back of –

181
00:13:46,880 --> 00:13:54,560
 I think back of – Deleuze makes a distinction, I can't remember where the Deleuze – the Beckett-Joyce distinction, right?

182
00:13:54,620 --> 00:14:09,380
 That on the question of identification, which is what we're talking about here, identifying something, like, that Joyce went the route of multiplication, which is just – I'm just going to put so much shit in Finnegan's Wake, you know, that it's going to be incomprehensible.

183
00:14:10,480 --> 00:14:16,760
 Whereas Beckett – and this was – Deleuze is more interested in this, and I am as well – Beckett went the route of subtraction.

184
00:14:16,900 --> 00:14:24,380
 Like, I'm just going to take everything out so that there's nothing, you know, I'm going to do an entire play that is a gesture or something, you know what I mean?

185
00:14:24,420 --> 00:14:31,100
 Like, there's going to be nothing – like, nothing will happen, nothing is going to – you know, so it's – those two different approaches.

186
00:14:31,240 --> 00:14:39,640
 Again, both of them are interested in problematizing, complicating the movements of identification, but they're really different styles, right?

187
00:14:39,640 --> 00:14:49,860
 Like, they're really different comportments to the project of complicating distinction or identification or recognition, again, it's – you know.

188
00:14:50,620 --> 00:14:55,300
 Well, on the face of it, you would think Deleuze would attach himself to Joyce, right?

189
00:14:55,360 --> 00:14:58,040
 Because that's more of a – that's more of an obvious multiplicity.

190
00:14:58,040 --> 00:14:58,960
 That's exactly right.

191
00:14:58,960 --> 00:15:08,260
 Right, but he's more interested in the subtractions of Beckett, which – I mean, when you actually look at Deleuze, that it does make sense that he would go to Beckett there.

192
00:15:08,260 --> 00:15:10,100
 But it takes a little bit of work.

193
00:15:10,180 --> 00:15:10,880
 It does.

194
00:15:11,040 --> 00:15:16,140
 It's not immediately – especially, you know, the proliferation that is Anti-Oedipus and Thousand Plateaus, right?

195
00:15:16,320 --> 00:15:19,640
 There's just such a profusion of different kinds of concepts.

196
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:22,700
 But I agree with you because I think of it like an interesting Kafka.

197
00:15:22,900 --> 00:15:26,040
 Kafka is like one of the least interesting humans, right?

198
00:15:26,080 --> 00:15:28,480
 I mean, in terms of his life, right?

199
00:15:30,240 --> 00:15:31,100
 Masochism, right?

200
00:15:31,140 --> 00:15:43,220
 I mean, he always – frequently will go the – I mean, one of my favorite phrases in my invention book was – it's – the first time I mentioned Deleuze and Guattari is I introduced them by saying,

201
00:15:43,580 --> 00:15:46,660
 as the great thinkers of confinement, Deleuze and Guattari.

202
00:15:46,960 --> 00:15:50,100
 And that's one of my favorite phrases because it's like that's it.

203
00:15:50,220 --> 00:15:51,560
 They are thinkers of confinement.

204
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:53,740
 Like, you want to talk about movement?

205
00:15:53,860 --> 00:15:56,120
 They are thinkers of movement, but it's intensive movement.

206
00:15:56,120 --> 00:16:10,060
 It's not – it's not – you know, because once you enter into this sort of identification, recognition types of movement, then it becomes the most you can do is just invent massively – you know, like go Finnegan's Wake, right?

207
00:16:10,060 --> 00:16:13,640
 That's the – Finnegan's Wake is kind of end point, I think, for –

208
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:16,420
 It's sort of the brain yes of the ass, right?

209
00:16:17,040 --> 00:16:17,660
 Right, yeah.

210
00:16:17,660 --> 00:16:19,580
 That's all that you can do.

211
00:16:20,440 --> 00:16:20,500
 Right.

212
00:16:21,240 --> 00:16:33,300
 See, that to me just makes me think that most of these people that are explicitly anti-dialectical, I understand why they make those decisions and why Deleuze and Foucault make those kind of cuts.

213
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:43,840
 But that's where, again, like the distinguishing between Deleuze and Hegel with that comment you just made about confinement, that makes it harder for me to think that distinction.

214
00:16:44,700 --> 00:16:48,180
 Because Hegel's obviously a thinker of confinement as well, right?

215
00:16:48,660 --> 00:16:52,900
 I mean, it's not just a multitude – it's not just everything's moving all at once.

216
00:16:53,080 --> 00:16:56,820
 He's thinking about, you know, explicit structures and the way they affect us.

217
00:16:56,820 --> 00:16:59,960
 And, I mean, again, it's way more explicitly phenomenological.

218
00:17:00,540 --> 00:17:07,740
 But the way that Becoming is articulated seems to be so similar in a sense.

219
00:17:10,820 --> 00:17:12,200
 I have to think about that one.

220
00:17:12,360 --> 00:17:16,060
 I mean, it doesn't immediately ring true for me, but I'm not going to discount it either.

221
00:17:16,280 --> 00:17:17,580
 I mean –

222
00:17:17,580 --> 00:17:22,140
 Well, it's like Foucault is also, like, you know, the anti-dialectical thinker par excellence.

223
00:17:22,620 --> 00:17:28,020
 And, like, I basically just figured that out, that he explicitly positioned himself that way.

224
00:17:28,080 --> 00:17:33,880
 Because in my readings of him, I'm like, I associate him with Butler, with Hegel.

225
00:17:34,280 --> 00:17:35,160
 And he didn't.

226
00:17:35,520 --> 00:17:37,260
 So I'm like, well, why didn't he?

227
00:17:37,660 --> 00:17:38,200
 I don't know.

228
00:17:38,260 --> 00:17:40,460
 It's still something I have to figure out, but a little more.

229
00:17:40,460 --> 00:17:44,520
 It seems to me to be a matter of what produces the confinement, right?

230
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:59,220
 And that, I mean, my orientation to Deleuze and those in that tradition, it's that confinement tends to be a byproduct of appropriation of between differences, right?

231
00:17:59,260 --> 00:18:06,320
 Like, an aggressive appropriation as opposed to an appropriation that's only made possible because of self-alienation.

232
00:18:06,320 --> 00:18:14,040
 So the confinement is the confinement or the stifling confinement of the one that must then self-alienate and reappropriate.

233
00:18:14,160 --> 00:18:27,100
 And that's just a different kind of confinement than, you know, the specific, you know, trajectory and angle and force and qualitative differences between two – one force that appropriates another, right?

234
00:18:27,360 --> 00:18:42,420
 Like, the confinement produced by the particular intersection of an appropriation is one kind of confinement as opposed to what I would take to be the much more claustrophobic confinement of a –

235
00:18:42,420 --> 00:18:52,880
 this is where I want to go back to think of – this is where I'm not being generous to Hegel again because I think of it as like this overabundant self-presence that has to self-alienate.

236
00:18:52,880 --> 00:19:02,360
 But that renders the self as a point which, again, I can do it seven times out of ten, but not ten out of ten when I'm reaching out.

237
00:19:02,560 --> 00:19:13,780
 Well, so, I mean, my – the thing that I'm thinking as you're talking there, Nathaniel, is like maybe this is just too simple, but there's a way in which – a baseline way in which –

238
00:19:13,780 --> 00:19:22,800
 I mean, this is the move that you make actually, Nate, in your proposal, the revised version of the proposal where you're a little more generous to Casey and Diane.

239
00:19:22,880 --> 00:19:32,240
 Again, by not making them ontological thinkers but making them ethical thinkers, that there's a sense in which, you know, maybe that's the sort of delusian orientation.

240
00:19:32,400 --> 00:19:42,360
 It's like given whatever sort of ontological circumstance, Kafka as a person doesn't move, you know, or the masochist as a figure doesn't move.

241
00:19:42,840 --> 00:19:46,400
 And that the claim is more about how to live, right?

242
00:19:46,980 --> 00:19:56,320
 How to live in a circumstance as opposed to, I don't know, like Hegel's – this is not – you know, it's spirit.

243
00:19:56,500 --> 00:20:02,920
 Spirit is not – he seems kind of in some ways maybe uninterested in how to live, you know.

244
00:20:02,920 --> 00:20:06,300
 At this juncture and, you know, in this book.

245
00:20:06,700 --> 00:20:17,720
 But that question is not really on the table for – this is just like, well, look, life is this voracious appropriation machine and I'm just going to lay out for you how it works.

246
00:20:18,280 --> 00:20:33,780
 As distinct from, you know, potentially the delusian orientation was, well, given that, here are ways to live that are less contributing to the voracious appropriation machine or at least attempt to interrupt it in some ways.

247
00:20:34,220 --> 00:20:34,360
 Yeah.

248
00:20:34,680 --> 00:20:48,700
 I think that's absolutely right and, I mean, it's – that's the reason why you can couple, like, Nietzsche and delus, maybe even put Foucault in there is because they're actually interested in modes of living that are other than resentment or whatever.

249
00:20:48,960 --> 00:20:49,200
 Right.

250
00:20:49,200 --> 00:20:57,400
 Whereas for Hegel, ethics is not really a choice or it's – rather ethics is incorporated into this system of appropriation.

251
00:20:57,940 --> 00:21:13,920
 So, again, like, even if there's – as nuanced as delus's or Nietzsche's ideas about that ethical intervention are, for Hegel, that's still – right, there's no real way out of the – like you guys are saying, the appropriation machine.

252
00:21:13,920 --> 00:21:23,620
 So, when you think there's a better mode of life, it still falls back into this movement of simplicity or negation or whatever, you know.

253
00:21:23,700 --> 00:21:40,260
 Well, this is where, like, the notion of better just functions very different for delus and Hegel as well because for Hegel, like, the notion of better is completely governed by, like, the transcendent progression of absolute spirit, in which case there is no choice.

254
00:21:40,260 --> 00:21:42,620
 It's just machinating, right?

255
00:21:43,160 --> 00:21:54,420
 But the notion of better is also problematic for delus at all as well because there is no transcendent metric by which to say better or worse.

256
00:21:54,680 --> 00:21:58,540
 And, like, when I was saying before about this different sense of confinement, it's like, no, no, no.

257
00:21:58,560 --> 00:22:09,720
 Given this intersection of forces, which produces a confinement, right, one idiosyncratic set of confinements that allow for different modes of life.

258
00:22:09,720 --> 00:22:18,660
 And then the ethical question is not, like, make that life better or worse, but experiment with the kinds of life that that confinement makes possible.

259
00:22:19,300 --> 00:22:19,380
 Right.

260
00:22:19,920 --> 00:22:21,820
 That's, to me, the distinction.

261
00:22:21,940 --> 00:22:25,560
 So, it's not about choosing a better form of life or finally figuring it out.

262
00:22:25,640 --> 00:22:30,960
 It's like, no, given the field, you know, the mandate is to experiment.

263
00:22:31,400 --> 00:22:34,460
 For those thinkers, the mandate is see what you can do.

264
00:22:35,320 --> 00:22:38,640
 And one possibility might be transforming the field, right?

265
00:22:38,760 --> 00:22:41,560
 Like, but that's nothing you're never going to know.

266
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:42,920
 And you're, you know.

267
00:22:43,640 --> 00:22:44,080
 Right.

268
00:22:44,360 --> 00:22:49,900
 Well, then, the question for me, then, is why can't we be, like, scope, just even broader scope.

269
00:22:50,020 --> 00:22:52,560
 Like, why can't we be generous to everyone?

270
00:22:53,040 --> 00:22:58,320
 Like, why do I have the impulse to glom onto Hegel rather than delus?

271
00:22:58,860 --> 00:23:03,080
 Why do you guys, why are you at least slightly more generous with delus?

272
00:23:03,180 --> 00:23:05,720
 Like, what engendered these decisions?

273
00:23:05,900 --> 00:23:11,280
 And why am I so invested in, you know, attaching myself to one rather than the other?

274
00:23:11,360 --> 00:23:12,480
 I mean, is that just, like, kind of.

275
00:23:13,000 --> 00:23:13,720
 It is the same.

276
00:23:13,820 --> 00:23:18,440
 And to me, it's the same question as making the distinctions about the people that you're reading and not reading.

277
00:23:18,440 --> 00:23:32,640
 Like, you know, for me, the project, I mean, it's an interesting idea because what happens if I try to, that's why you should, I mean, in a sense, go after delus, but also go after Hegel as well.

278
00:23:32,700 --> 00:23:33,040
 Right.

279
00:23:33,180 --> 00:23:33,400
 Right.

280
00:23:33,400 --> 00:23:52,040
 But think of an interesting way of doing it, not just the sort of, like, okay, yes, everyone says this is a voracious machine-like thing, but maybe, and that's in many ways I feel like what I'm struggling with is how do we understand the projects of these other folks like delus, like Foucault?

281
00:23:52,240 --> 00:24:02,820
 I mean, as you pose the question there of, I always saw him as part of this, you know, this lineage, but he didn't see himself as part of that lineage, and why not?

282
00:24:04,100 --> 00:24:05,420
 What was up for him?

283
00:24:05,620 --> 00:24:19,520
 And even if it turns out that what you discover is, well, because he had a kind of poor reading of Hegel that was based on these traditional notions of totalitarian statehood, come up with a better one, right?

284
00:24:19,780 --> 00:24:19,960
 Yeah.

285
00:24:19,960 --> 00:24:32,540
 Come up with better, and to me, this sounds kind of like a better one, which is, given the ontological condition of negation, experiment with other possibilities.

286
00:24:33,580 --> 00:24:34,020
 Right.

287
00:24:34,440 --> 00:24:34,800
 Yeah.

288
00:24:34,900 --> 00:24:35,160
 You know?

289
00:24:35,220 --> 00:24:35,340
 Yeah.

290
00:24:36,360 --> 00:24:49,680
 But this is, I mean, my question is this is, I see where, I mean, forget about it as a mandate, I just see how experimentation is possible within the ontological field.

291
00:24:49,680 --> 00:24:51,200
 That Deleuze sets up, right?

292
00:24:51,200 --> 00:24:51,420
 Yeah.

293
00:24:51,520 --> 00:24:56,180
 Because, I mean, I don't even know what it would mean to experiment with it.

294
00:24:56,340 --> 00:25:02,860
 Like, there's no, like, one of my fundamental questions has been, can there be right or wrong turns in here?

295
00:25:02,940 --> 00:25:07,280
 Or, like, just to make it more radical, can there be turns, right?

296
00:25:07,300 --> 00:25:07,460
 Right.

297
00:25:07,520 --> 00:25:08,600
 This just seems like it's a straight road.

298
00:25:08,600 --> 00:25:10,420
 Well, that's the dead end question that you asked before.

299
00:25:10,560 --> 00:25:10,740
 Yeah.

300
00:25:10,980 --> 00:25:11,280
 Yeah.

301
00:25:11,520 --> 00:25:12,480
 Are there dead ends?

302
00:25:12,560 --> 00:25:13,580
 Like, do people do it wrong?

303
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:25,660
 Whereas I would even, you know, intensify your earlier claim about, you know, changing the field as a possible mode of experimentation with a kind of confinement and not knowing whether you're doing it or not.

304
00:25:25,660 --> 00:25:36,520
 I would go radically the other direction and say, you're changing the field no matter what you do and how you, you're experimenting with it regardless, irregardless, it's now officially a word.

305
00:25:37,680 --> 00:25:39,620
 Regardless of what you do.

306
00:25:39,620 --> 00:25:40,520
 Because you said it?

307
00:25:41,820 --> 00:25:44,040
 No, because the OED adopted it.

308
00:25:45,600 --> 00:25:49,800
 They decided enough dumb fuckers have started using it thinking it was a word that we've got to.

309
00:25:50,340 --> 00:25:51,380
 We'll just put it in there.

310
00:25:51,700 --> 00:25:52,940
 We've just got to put it in there, yeah.

311
00:25:53,100 --> 00:25:54,440
 I mean, it's a big fucking book.

312
00:25:54,540 --> 00:25:55,720
 What difference does another word do it?

313
00:25:55,720 --> 00:25:56,680
 Yeah, he gives a shit.

314
00:25:58,820 --> 00:26:04,900
 But, like, the field can't help but be remade.

315
00:26:05,320 --> 00:26:12,980
 And it's, like, it would be very difficult to imagine what a straight line would look like in that.

316
00:26:13,700 --> 00:26:15,240
 Like, I think maybe that's the biggest difference.

317
00:26:15,380 --> 00:26:19,820
 I think it's difficult to imagine a straight line within a Deleuzian ontology.

318
00:26:19,820 --> 00:26:25,300
 And it's very difficult to imagine a turn within Hegel's field.

319
00:26:26,860 --> 00:26:33,240
 Yeah, I mean, what Hegel offers me specifically for my project is, like, just an anti-utopianism.

320
00:26:33,820 --> 00:26:46,580
 So, what I sense in Barad and even in Butler and people that kind of react against some of the, what I guess, fatalism sort of of Hegel is what I want to lean into.

321
00:26:46,580 --> 00:26:51,660
 Because it just seems, I don't know, either truer or more pragmatic or something.

322
00:26:51,980 --> 00:27:03,700
 Because what, the moves that Butler tries to make away from Hegel ends up simply, again, like, not, I feel like I keep emphasizing the appropriation machine in a bad way.

323
00:27:03,980 --> 00:27:07,300
 But, like, for me, it functions as a warning.

324
00:27:07,460 --> 00:27:23,420
 Like, every time you think you're transforming the field or whatever, every time you have an inclination or a sense that something is being transformed or that you're operating on the side of progressive change.

325
00:27:23,500 --> 00:27:25,240
 Which I'm not saying, like, Deleuz does or anyone.

326
00:27:25,420 --> 00:27:28,320
 But people like Barad are invested in those kind of moves.

327
00:27:28,420 --> 00:27:36,720
 It's like, for Hegel, that's, it's, it's both untenable and, like, kind of a necessary reaction to the dynamics of negation.

328
00:27:37,180 --> 00:27:41,860
 You know, so, like, that, that reach for progress is both necessary and impossible.

329
00:27:42,040 --> 00:27:44,040
 It's that constant movement.

330
00:27:44,140 --> 00:27:47,700
 And I can see how that's, like, not attractive for people.

331
00:27:47,900 --> 00:27:56,160
 I mean, like, it's not, I don't think it's attractive for most people even in everyday life to think that everything is sort of incorporated under a system of negation.

332
00:27:56,520 --> 00:27:59,960
 It's like, that's not something that, like, it's not like a motto that everyone runs around with.

333
00:28:00,440 --> 00:28:03,960
 But, um, I don't know if there is a progressivism here, though.

334
00:28:04,080 --> 00:28:04,480
 Is there not?

335
00:28:04,540 --> 00:28:11,040
 I mean, like, everything is moving toward the absolute consciousness of, of manifestation and consciousness of, of God.

336
00:28:11,220 --> 00:28:13,380
 So, like, I do get, like, you know.

337
00:28:13,380 --> 00:28:14,500
 Artificial intelligence, baby.

338
00:28:14,640 --> 00:28:15,380
 That's Hegel's.

339
00:28:15,780 --> 00:28:17,420
 When Hegel plays it out, there it is.

340
00:28:17,440 --> 00:28:18,280
 Predicted it, yeah.

341
00:28:18,280 --> 00:28:29,540
 I mean, the bubble that is getting popped is that, you know, people think that they can produce progress that is different from, you know, the sort of downward slope.

342
00:28:29,840 --> 00:28:34,860
 Like, they can be the one that saves the thing or they can be the one that diverts it onto the right track.

343
00:28:34,960 --> 00:28:39,900
 And they've made, you know, following their, their plan is better than the other one.

344
00:28:39,900 --> 00:28:44,940
 And, like, you know, Hegel's just like, like, Drake.

345
00:28:45,160 --> 00:28:45,740
 God's plan.

346
00:28:45,860 --> 00:28:46,460
 God's plan.

347
00:28:46,840 --> 00:28:47,460
 God's plan.

