00:28:51,160 --> 00:28:51,580
 Go ahead, man.

352
00:28:51,600 --> 00:28:51,900
 Go ahead.

353
00:28:52,240 --> 00:28:58,380
 It's just, like, I see that reading and I, again, like, I think that that's fair and viable.

354
00:28:59,020 --> 00:29:05,020
 It's just, for me, absolute spirit doesn't signal progress in that, in a traditional sense of, like, getting better.

355
00:29:05,400 --> 00:29:07,480
 Absolute spirit maybe is better for the philosopher.

356
00:29:07,700 --> 00:29:10,440
 It's not, it's not better for life or for people.

357
00:29:10,540 --> 00:29:13,980
 It's just simply a, it's a, it's a progression in thinking.

358
00:29:14,200 --> 00:29:16,200
 But there's no, again, there's no comfort.

359
00:29:16,600 --> 00:29:19,640
 There's no, you can't rest in that space.

360
00:29:19,740 --> 00:29:22,520
 That's when you actually, that's when you have to invent and experiment.

361
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:25,340
 That's, to me, when experimentation happens in Hegel.

362
00:29:25,580 --> 00:29:31,020
 Once you reach that reflexive point where you're like, oh, this is actually all a movement of self.

363
00:29:31,180 --> 00:29:33,820
 There's no outside reality separate from me.

364
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:36,440
 So now I can start playing around, right?

365
00:29:36,500 --> 00:29:40,420
 Like, so that's when the play starts happening in Hegel.

366
00:29:40,420 --> 00:29:48,860
 Okay, because what I was going to, because what I was going to ask you a moment ago, which I think is a very, I mean, it's a question for your project and for where you are right now.

