 Because I'm reading them like primary sources.

404
00:32:28,840 --> 00:32:34,640
 I'm reading, I'm reading like a secondary source of Barad, which that's when it's like, okay, this is not really.

405
00:32:34,940 --> 00:32:36,340
 No one's gaining anything out of this.

406
00:32:36,520 --> 00:32:42,400
 But the better, some of the better rhetorical theorists in our field, you can read them like you would read Barad or Hegel or whoever.

407
00:32:42,560 --> 00:32:45,840
 So I think there's still, you can have productive commentary with them.

408
00:32:46,280 --> 00:32:46,440
 Yeah.

409
00:32:46,700 --> 00:32:47,880
 I want you to come after me.

410
00:32:47,960 --> 00:32:49,160
 Come after the invention book.

411
00:32:49,360 --> 00:32:51,100
 I would be, I'm being totally serious.

412
00:32:52,060 --> 00:32:59,720
 Like, if there's something there, I'm not saying you got, I mean, but I'm just saying, like, so as the sort of Deleuze rep in the field, you know, like, I'd be interested in that.

413
00:32:59,720 --> 00:33:03,700
 Because, because it's, it's, it really is interesting to me.

414
00:33:03,700 --> 00:33:06,260
 And I do, like I said, I share the impulse.

415
00:33:06,920 --> 00:33:14,320
 And I just, for me, I never wanted to, so for instance, earlier versions of the invention book, like the dissertation version, were much more polemical.

416
00:33:14,840 --> 00:33:21,940
 And a lot of the stuff that, there's residues of stuff on B-sicker in there and a couple of other things where I just kind of took them out or toned them down.

417
00:33:22,040 --> 00:33:27,780
 Because I realized, for me, I was like, actually, it's that move that I want to try to forestall.

418
00:33:27,920 --> 00:33:30,720
 And it's the move of saying, I'm not them, right?

419
00:33:30,840 --> 00:33:34,760
 I'm not, or the thinking I'm doing is not aligned with that.

420
00:33:35,060 --> 00:33:44,980
 And what became interesting to me was, and it was early on in the diss writing process, and it was the, oh God, the audience addressed, audience, the Eid and Lunds folks.

421
00:33:44,980 --> 00:33:45,720
 Invoked, yeah.

422
00:33:46,120 --> 00:33:56,680
 Right, so those two, and that's, I mean, I just find that to be an insipid and a perfect example of this kind of liberal ethos that masquerades itself as a kind of intellectual project.

423
00:33:56,840 --> 00:34:04,160
 And it, I mean, I, honestly, I just remember reading that for the first time and being like, this is so frustrating and angering to me.

424
00:34:04,720 --> 00:34:11,660
 Not just the piece itself, but also how it was taken up is like, oh, this is a wonderful example of inclusion and all this kind of stuff.

425
00:34:11,940 --> 00:34:14,580
 And I really want to smack it down.

426
00:34:14,580 --> 00:34:25,260
 And the first chapter that I wrote, the chapter, I can't remember which one it was, but I ended up, so I started off with a kind of polemical takedown of that.

427
00:34:25,260 --> 00:34:42,540
 And as I wrote through it and continued on, it ended up revisiting some of that, and where Eid and Lunsford ended up having kind of like anticipated my objections and done, and sort of done something to prevent me, prevent those kinds of objections.

428
00:34:42,540 --> 00:34:59,200
 And I was like, wow, this is a way weirder space to be in where I no longer dislike that progressive liberalism because it actually has hinges that I believe they probably didn't ever think of.

429
00:34:59,440 --> 00:34:59,600
 Right.

430
00:34:59,840 --> 00:35:00,840
 But they're there.

431
00:35:00,840 --> 00:35:03,240
 I mean, I didn't just invent them, you know.

432
00:35:03,840 --> 00:35:09,360
 And so it was this interesting moment of, oh, my God, I don't know who Eid and Lunsford are anymore.

433
00:35:09,800 --> 00:35:14,040
 And therefore, I don't know who I am in relation to them anymore.

434
00:35:14,260 --> 00:35:17,920
 And now, this is precisely the productive space.

435
00:35:18,520 --> 00:35:36,020
 And so it required the polemical, but it also required the undermining of the polemical using them, right, to get into that space of where what I just said mirrors what you were saying about absolute spirit is the place where the shit can happen, right?

436
00:35:36,020 --> 00:35:43,600
 Where the sort of pure contingency of multiplicity, whatever, that was my sort of experience working through it.

437
00:35:44,180 --> 00:35:48,500
 And, I mean, who knows how you're going to go through it, but it's just an interesting move.

438
00:35:48,580 --> 00:36:01,300
 When you get to that thinking of indistinction, and it's still, at least for me, it's not like I got there and I lived there and I'm now there and it's a fucking, you know, put up a homeowner sign or something.

439
00:36:01,300 --> 00:36:10,960
 It's like, it's always work, in a sense, to get into that space where I don't think I'm distinguishing myself from something.

440
00:36:11,180 --> 00:36:12,860
 But I always see it as a draw.

441
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:27,840
 It's like, how can I use this thing, and even our interactions like this, how can I use this thing in order to induce in me that disillusion of desire for recognition, in a sense, you know?

442
00:36:28,380 --> 00:36:32,740
 So I'm just thinking about the different ways of producing that movement.

443
00:36:32,920 --> 00:36:36,920
 And it sounds like it, at least for you, starts with the polemical.

444
00:36:38,280 --> 00:36:38,840
 It did.

445
00:36:39,060 --> 00:36:49,380
 What you've done is, like, you do the polemical work, and then you, like, do it against the strongest version of the target that you can create.

446
00:36:49,680 --> 00:37:01,380
 And then once you've rendered the indistinction through the work of the polemical, you subtract the polemicism and attribute the positive value back to this indistinct, you know?

447
00:37:01,380 --> 00:37:10,360
 Well, because it really does get to the point where it's like, oh, fuck, all those things that I said that got me here don't really make sense anymore.

448
00:37:10,360 --> 00:37:22,300
 Given the generous reading that I've done and sort of, you know, been forced to do, that given the generous reading, the ungenerous stuff that got me there doesn't make sense.

449
00:37:23,100 --> 00:37:28,360
 What about, like, another way of doing it without subtracting the polemics?

450
00:37:28,560 --> 00:37:37,820
 Allow, like, start with the polemical and then let it intensify to the point where it becomes indistinguishable from the polemicized.

451
00:37:38,260 --> 00:37:47,980
 And then you're in this fun, like, you can be in this very fun place of almost, like, ironic mania where you can't tell the one from the other.

452
00:37:48,560 --> 00:38:01,320
 And, like, just as a pedagogical move for the reader, like, to be able to follow the, you know, this absolute distinction into this almost manic indistinction.

453
00:38:03,260 --> 00:38:04,500
 That's what I was going to say.

454
00:38:04,820 --> 00:38:15,120
 Yeah, like, the polemic and the indistinction, I think, at least under the Hegelian or maybe the Zizekian comportment, those don't have to be separate moments, right?

455
00:38:15,120 --> 00:38:21,740
 Because, I mean, someone like Zizek especially, he's so polemical, he's just striking people down, right?

456
00:38:22,260 --> 00:38:24,460
 Thinkers after thinkers, just, this is what they missed.

457
00:38:24,740 --> 00:38:26,820
 This is how they absolutely missed the point.

458
00:38:27,280 --> 00:38:31,280
 But that, it comes back to his own project in some way.

459
00:38:31,280 --> 00:38:35,600
 So, that's like, he's almost, he's chastising everybody, including himself in that picture.

460
00:38:35,740 --> 00:38:42,140
 So, it's almost like the polemic is just variegated to this point of, like, at a certain point, you don't really know the target.

461
00:38:42,520 --> 00:38:43,580
 It's like, we're all the target.

462
00:38:44,040 --> 00:38:44,720
 Everybody's the target.

463
00:38:44,820 --> 00:38:46,260
 Myself is the target, you know.

464
00:38:47,060 --> 00:38:53,540
 But that movement would have to be, that movement would have to, it couldn't be dismissive, right?

465
00:38:53,540 --> 00:38:59,760
 It would have to be a polemic that could, that could never arrive at the moment of dismissal.

466
00:38:59,840 --> 00:39:09,320
 Because the, the more it tried to render to the distinction that can be dismissed, the more that distinction becomes indistinct, right?

467
00:39:09,480 --> 00:39:18,000
 That would, I mean, to me, that's what would, that, the movement couldn't, the movement couldn't be like, dismiss this, dismiss this, dismiss this.

468
00:39:18,340 --> 00:39:19,320
 Right, it can't, yes.

469
00:39:19,760 --> 00:39:27,360
 Well, I mean, it can be, but that's going to short circuit the, the sort of generous indistinguishability moment.

470
00:39:27,560 --> 00:39:28,380
 I mean, it's going to make that.

471
00:39:28,640 --> 00:39:33,300
 But I think of, like, in, it's the chapter that I'm thinking about, so it was the audience chapter in the invention book.

472
00:39:33,720 --> 00:39:40,900
 And I start off with, like, you know, the popular phrase of one must, the writer should consider their audience when they write.

473
00:39:41,380 --> 00:39:47,140
 And I go through a little bit of, like, that is a meaningless, worthless statement.

474
00:39:47,320 --> 00:39:52,360
 Like, it doesn't say anything, and yet everybody thinks it's this really important message, but what could it actually mean?

475
00:39:52,360 --> 00:40:04,260
 But by the end, I just fully endorsed that slogan as being, well, you know, that's, that's the lesson that I've learned, is that the audience, the audience, or the writer must consider their audience when they write.

476
00:40:04,680 --> 00:40:15,920
 And that, that, that sentence now has so many possible senses to it, and is so diffuse and amorphous as to not offer any solace or comfort or even direction.

477
00:40:17,200 --> 00:40:38,520
 And that, to me, was, that was the interesting thing of the, the change in the sense of this slogan that, you know, people say all of the time from one of, think about other people when you're composing to, like, you know, whatever the fuck, you know, this kind of massive indistinguishability as the space for invention or whatever.

478
00:40:39,320 --> 00:40:48,000
 But, but, but the, the important movement in that is that, you know, the slogan at the beginning becomes, like, a maxim, like, run this machine, right?

479
00:40:48,120 --> 00:41:02,380
 And then by the time it becomes a slogan again, it's like, it becomes a provocation for having to, like, think, and you don't know because it's inhabited, taken on so many things, you don't know where it's going to take you.

480
00:41:02,380 --> 00:41:13,100
 Let's read, let's read, let's read that one for, let's read that chapter for the next time, because, I mean, I haven't read it in 15 years, but I, I just remember the writing of that, and it really, because that's the Eden Lunsford stuff as well.

481
00:41:13,500 --> 00:41:17,360
 And so we'll see if it still is, still remain, if I got all the polemics out.

482
00:41:17,540 --> 00:41:29,060
 But that's what that chapter was, was it ended up being this, like, slogan that at the beginning is an untenable slogan that by the end is, like, the only thing that you can possibly say about writing, you know?

483
00:41:29,320 --> 00:41:30,460
 Right, yeah.

484
00:41:30,700 --> 00:41:36,340
 I'd be interested to hear your guys' responses to the movement of that chapter.

485
00:41:37,160 --> 00:41:55,840
 Yeah, and I mean, the movement from endorsement to complication to kind of provisional endorsement to complication, I mean, that's what interests me, and that's sort of what at least Zizek's version of Hegel provides, is that there's no simple endorsement of a mode of thinking or a paradigm or whatever.

486
00:41:55,840 --> 00:42:07,080
 And that's what I react against in the Barads and people like that, is that there's one singular endorsement of this mode without a constant kind of turning over of that mode of thinking.

487
00:42:07,300 --> 00:42:14,600
 So it's like, that's the main thing for me, is like, if you're going to endorse anything, it's the process of interrogating your own endorsements.

488
00:42:14,700 --> 00:42:16,840
 Right, the problem is the dogmatism.

489
00:42:17,200 --> 00:42:17,620
 Yeah, yeah.

490
00:42:17,620 --> 00:42:29,000
 Even if the dogmatism is not, like, strident and, like, you know, shouting at the front of a crowd, like, it's still implicit in the thinking that, yeah, I mean, I agree with you.

491
00:42:29,180 --> 00:42:42,780
 I mean, that's where, for me, very influential for me coming to Deleuze, because the first thing that I ever read was the Foucault, because I'd spent my first semester of graduate school, I just read everything by Foucault that was translated at the time.

492
00:42:43,180 --> 00:42:49,880
 And then Foucault, it was my second semester of master's program, where I read the Foucault intro to Antioedipus, right?

493
00:42:49,880 --> 00:43:06,260
 And the whole message of that preface is, this is the book that's an introduction to the anti-fascist life, and recognizing the ways in which all the little molecular fascisms that comprise the directions of our thinking.

494
00:43:06,560 --> 00:43:21,300
 So that informed so much of how I went into Deleuze, because I was like, well, that's exactly the project that interests me, is, I mean, we don't have to call it fascist, we can call it dogmatic, as you're saying, or earlier I was calling this, you know, moral, the moral high ground or whatever.

495
00:43:21,300 --> 00:43:22,960
 But it is, it is that, right?

496
00:43:23,040 --> 00:43:25,500
 Like, that sense of, here's the thing to do.

497
00:43:25,560 --> 00:43:36,540
 But it's interesting to me, because what appeals to you is not a kind of wavering quality, it's actually a dogmatic commitment to non-dogmatism.

498
00:43:36,560 --> 00:43:37,080
 Mm-hmm.

499
00:43:37,720 --> 00:43:38,080
 Right?

500
00:43:38,440 --> 00:43:47,360
 Like, and, but that's not necessarily a contradiction, I mean, it's only a contradiction logically, like, I see that as, like, this sort of insistent point.

501
00:43:47,520 --> 00:43:51,860
 But that's where I'm going to come back for you, in terms of your project, is, like, what are you going to make, right?

502
00:43:51,940 --> 00:43:59,980
 Like, so I get how that's fun to smack, not fun, I don't want to, I don't want to diminish it at all.

503
00:44:00,220 --> 00:44:00,420
 Right.

504
00:44:00,500 --> 00:44:12,320
 I get the draw and the appeal of the smackdown, and I would say, like, for me, speaking and, like, in class, that's 90% of what I do, is the smackdown of the thing that thinks it's found the answer.

505
00:44:13,080 --> 00:44:19,680
 But for me, at least, writing has always been, at least academic writing has always been, I don't want to write that shit up.

506
00:44:19,760 --> 00:44:22,040
 It's just, it feels gross to me to write that up.

507
00:44:22,100 --> 00:44:26,140
 I'm always interested in writing up something that's the next step, right?

508
00:44:26,220 --> 00:44:27,880
 Like, so, what do we make now?

509
00:44:38,540 --> 00:44:49,040
 Part of the fun of the experiment is, you know, because you don't propose the dogma in place of the dogma that you're smacking down,

510
00:44:49,040 --> 00:45:06,300
 or that if there is one there, it's just the dogmatic adherence to smacking down the dogma is, like, I mean, that could be an interesting line of flight just to see what happens when the criticism isn't for the sake of some, you know, on the horizon, you know, dogmas.

511
00:45:06,460 --> 00:45:13,060
 Like, what happens when that becomes, what can relentless criticism and negation do?

512
00:45:13,600 --> 00:45:16,100
 That's Adorno, that's negative dialectic.

513
00:45:16,600 --> 00:45:16,780
 Right.

514
00:45:16,900 --> 00:45:28,840
 I mean, it may, by the way, I'm not saying it's not Hegel and it's not Zizek, I'm just saying, like, that's, to me, that was the thing that I got from Adorno's negative dialectic, is just like, oh my God, this is just relentless criticism, you know?

515
00:45:29,380 --> 00:45:35,880
 And then criticism of the criticism, and then criticism of the criticism of the, you know, like, there's no sublation, there's no off-hebong.

516
00:45:35,980 --> 00:45:46,420
 In his terms, the sublation or off-hebong was the positive moment of growth, right, or progress, and that's what, he's effectively trying to take that moment out of Hegel, right?

517
00:45:47,640 --> 00:45:52,920
 So, that there's, and it's just, man, I mean, it's cool, it's really cool.

518
00:45:53,360 --> 00:45:55,820
 I mean, from my perspective, that's going to make something.

519
00:45:55,940 --> 00:46:00,540
 There's no way that that can't make something, but I don't know what it is, right?

520
00:46:00,680 --> 00:46:01,720
 And that could be the fun of the experience.

521
00:46:01,720 --> 00:46:02,240
 Which is okay.

522
00:46:02,800 --> 00:46:04,300
 You could call it a method of reading.

523
00:46:04,300 --> 00:46:04,520
 Well, that makes it fun.

524
00:46:04,780 --> 00:46:08,700
 You could call it a method of interpretation, but yeah, I mean, that's the basic, right?

525
00:46:08,780 --> 00:46:14,160
 The relentless suspicion of the movement of discourse, of conceptuality, right?

526
00:46:14,240 --> 00:46:23,880
 The constant, like, turning over of your own propositions, seeing what they do in different contexts, seeing if they still function the way you wanted to at first, right?

527
00:46:23,880 --> 00:46:29,780
 So, that ruthless or relentless self-consciousness, I mean, to me, that's, I don't see that anywhere.

528
00:46:29,780 --> 00:46:34,200
 So, at least in terms of a comportment, right?

529
00:46:34,260 --> 00:46:36,840
 If I'm offering a comportment, that is something.

530
00:46:37,760 --> 00:46:38,300
 No, no, no.

531
00:46:38,300 --> 00:46:39,500
 Here's another way of putting it.

532
00:46:39,640 --> 00:46:48,600
 Putting it in some of the language that you had earlier is, like, you, what you really liked about, what you really like about Hegel is that he doesn't offer you the solace of rest, right?

533
00:46:48,900 --> 00:46:55,260
 That there isn't any place where you can be like, all right, we're better now because everything is under the process of the self-alienation.

534
00:46:55,640 --> 00:47:02,580
 And that's precisely the bubble that you like to pop is that people just want to find somewhere to have, like, to rest.

535
00:47:02,740 --> 00:47:12,820
 And if anything, if there is a moralism, for you, it seems to be like rest is, one, the figure of rest is just not on the table, right?

536
00:47:12,880 --> 00:47:13,620
 It's impossible.

537
00:47:14,180 --> 00:47:15,280
 And it's not desirable either.

538
00:47:15,360 --> 00:47:16,660
 That would be death, right?

539
00:47:17,180 --> 00:47:17,300
 Right.

540
00:47:18,180 --> 00:47:18,480
 Exactly.

541
00:47:18,480 --> 00:47:29,520
 So, the only response to completely short-circuit the desire to rest, to find, you know, the good plateau is relentless criticism.

542
00:47:29,900 --> 00:47:33,140
 You know what one of your targets then should be?

543
00:47:33,760 --> 00:47:34,500
 Because I like this.

544
00:47:34,580 --> 00:47:35,400
 I mean, this sounds cool.

545
00:47:35,560 --> 00:47:40,860
 Like, one of your targets should be, think of, like, the Latour and the Kate Hales, like, a decade ago.

546
00:47:40,920 --> 00:47:48,240
 And there seems to be this kind of giving up of the so-called hermeneutics of suspicion because it didn't really pan out to get us.

547
00:47:48,480 --> 00:47:50,980
 And you're like, yeah, it wasn't fucking suspicious enough, right?

548
00:47:51,560 --> 00:47:52,280
 Exactly, yeah.

549
00:47:52,280 --> 00:47:58,640
 You know, I mean, that's, you know, your claim is exactly the opposite of theirs, of that it didn't go far enough.

550
00:47:58,640 --> 00:48:06,920
 And so, instead of giving that up and siding with the making of stuff, instead it's like, no, let's double down on the suspicion.

551
00:48:07,660 --> 00:48:13,260
 And we need to even be suspicious of our suspicions and, you know, et cetera.

552
00:48:14,000 --> 00:48:14,400
 Exactly.

553
00:48:14,800 --> 00:48:20,480
 And, again, it's not like, it's not like at the end of that, like, we get to the best orientation.

554
00:48:21,120 --> 00:48:25,920
 It's like, I mean, you can't guarantee anything within that dynamic of suspicion.

555
00:48:26,280 --> 00:48:28,480
 There's nothing guaranteed or there's no comfort.

556
00:48:28,720 --> 00:48:37,960
 So, again, it's like, right, like, Nathaniel, you're saying, there's no, I'm not, I'm both critiquing these resting points that people glom onto.

557
00:48:37,960 --> 00:48:46,780
 But you also have to articulate those as basically necessary moments of discourse or at least, like, understandable.

558
00:48:47,040 --> 00:48:49,640
 Like, right, you can diagnose them within this movement.

559
00:48:49,640 --> 00:48:54,340
 Because everybody needs to territorialize in Deleuze's terms.

560
00:48:54,480 --> 00:49:00,840
 It's just that once you reify that one of those moments, that's where I find there to be trouble.

561
00:49:00,840 --> 00:49:09,180
 Well, so it's not just the delusion that one has found rest.

562
00:49:09,500 --> 00:49:13,880
 That is more profoundly you're criticizing the drive or the desire to find the rest.

563
00:49:14,560 --> 00:49:14,960
 Right.

564
00:49:15,520 --> 00:49:15,920
 Right.

565
00:49:16,060 --> 00:49:17,140
 We want what's bad for us.

566
00:49:17,880 --> 00:49:19,020
 We want what's going to kill us.

567
00:49:19,240 --> 00:49:20,160
 There's the death drive.

568
00:49:20,960 --> 00:49:21,200
 Right.

569
00:49:21,240 --> 00:49:23,380
 We want to arrest the process of becoming.

570
00:49:25,220 --> 00:49:25,620
 Yeah.

571
00:49:26,080 --> 00:49:33,060
 Well, it's just such a strange, like, when you really think about it, because it's like you both need those resting points and you also can't have a final one.

572
00:49:33,140 --> 00:49:34,380
 Because, like you're saying, it would be death.

573
00:49:34,900 --> 00:49:42,000
 So the death drive is precisely the suspension of any final resting point, for Freud at least, right?

574
00:49:42,060 --> 00:49:42,880
 So it's like that.

575
00:49:43,260 --> 00:49:46,920
 Again, you probably can't think of it in points, but it does kind of lend itself to that.

576
00:49:46,920 --> 00:49:52,200
 Where, like, you have a, you have a, you have a territorialization and then you destroy it and then you bring, you bring yourself to a new one.

577
00:49:52,360 --> 00:50:01,100
 It's clearly not linear like that, but, but this is the, like, the language of de-territorialization, like, nothing is ever territorialized, right?

578
00:50:01,180 --> 00:50:02,380
 It's only the process of.

579
00:50:02,440 --> 00:50:03,320
 Nothing is ever a-territorialized.

580
00:50:03,420 --> 00:50:03,700
 Exactly.

581
00:50:03,780 --> 00:50:04,420
 Right, exactly.

582
00:50:04,640 --> 00:50:18,420
 And I think that's, you know, I, you know, I think that you can definitely say in this Hegelian sense that there is always, you know, a, the, the, the production of, or there is the process of resting, right?

583
00:50:18,420 --> 00:50:20,400
 Or, like, or arresting, right?

584
00:50:20,740 --> 00:50:26,420
 But it's, it never stabilizes into a point and, man, do people want it.

585
00:50:26,800 --> 00:50:32,700
 And that's, that should be the thing that we have to relentlessly combat and be on guard against.

586
00:50:33,220 --> 00:50:33,660
 Right.

587
00:50:33,980 --> 00:50:37,360
 Because even logically, that stability lends itself to death.

588
00:50:37,920 --> 00:50:41,020
 Like, just within the system, you can't access that stability.

589
00:50:41,560 --> 00:50:41,660
 Yeah.

590
00:50:41,900 --> 00:50:43,520
 That stasis is untenable.

591
00:50:44,240 --> 00:50:44,360
 Yeah.

592
00:50:45,200 --> 00:50:47,880
 And, yeah, for some fucking weird reason, people want it.

593
00:50:48,800 --> 00:50:51,680
 You have to do a lot of work to maintain things as they are.

594
00:50:51,800 --> 00:50:53,460
 It's never just, right.

595
00:50:53,600 --> 00:51:00,940
 Which is, I always use the language of, of, you know, the closest you can get to that stability is cancer, right?

596
00:51:01,180 --> 00:51:09,640
 Which is the constant laborious reproduction of the same, which is never quite the same, and it takes over everything, right?

597
00:51:09,700 --> 00:51:16,820
 That even, I, that, that to me is the closest, like, the thing that people, people want their own cancer.

598
00:51:16,960 --> 00:51:26,440
 They, they, they want to reproduce the condition, like, some kind of ideal condition that in its very repetition is never, ever the same.

599
00:51:27,080 --> 00:51:33,300
 But it's, but isn't there a difference between places of rest and places of moral superiority, right?

600
00:51:33,400 --> 00:51:46,800
 Like, I mean, to, to me, the idea of rest, I mean, if we're thinking of it in those terms of, like, movement and rest, um, or relative movements or whatever, like, I, I don't have a problem with rest.

601
00:51:46,840 --> 00:51:51,000
 I don't have a problem with, like, okay, you can't sprint 24-7, right?

602
00:51:51,080 --> 00:51:54,360
 Like, you know, I mean, you can't.

603
00:51:54,360 --> 00:51:57,420
 I mean, you've got to, you've got to rest in order to be able to sprint.

604
00:51:57,960 --> 00:52:09,360
 Um, but there, there's a difference between that and a lot of what drives, um, the projects that you're talking about isn't so much rest as, like, certainty, right?

605
00:52:09,460 --> 00:52:20,180
 Like, the, the, the belief that I have the answer or that I know the solution or correctness in some ways, truth, you would say.

606
00:52:20,180 --> 00:52:23,180
 Which is, which, I mean, is kind of a resting.

607
00:52:23,540 --> 00:52:24,640
 It's a kind of rest.

608
00:52:24,780 --> 00:52:25,800
 Resting in certainty.

609
00:52:26,240 --> 00:52:29,620
 Resting in the, the grounds of your system that you set up.

610
00:52:29,740 --> 00:52:39,880
 That, see, that's, that's one of the main issues I have with Barad is that even though it's this, like, very strange, diffracted ontology, there's still a grounds to that ontology.

611
00:52:40,280 --> 00:52:42,160
 And it's, it's materiality, it's relationality.

612
00:52:42,200 --> 00:52:43,860
 And so, she rests in that, right?

613
00:52:43,920 --> 00:52:49,960
 She's, she's completely at, at peace with her, uh, with her ontological framework, right?

614
00:52:50,020 --> 00:52:58,380
 But the, the idea here is you want to come up with a, a notion of rest then that isn't stable, right?

615
00:52:58,380 --> 00:53:08,360
 Like, that, that, so if, you know, what absolute spirit or pure contingency or pure negation or whatever would be a sense of stasis that's not immobile, right?

616
00:53:08,400 --> 00:53:12,020
 It's not, it doesn't simply repeat the same and it never could.

617
00:53:12,100 --> 00:53:13,460
 It can't even imagine that.

618
00:53:14,060 --> 00:53:23,960
 Um, so if, if, if rest then is refigured as a particular style of movement, um, then it would be less, less troubling, right?

619
00:53:24,160 --> 00:53:38,320
 And less, and less, um, um, um, it'd be more difficult to, um, uh, for a place like, rest like that to grant anybody certainty.

620
00:53:38,320 --> 00:53:46,440
 Because I do agree with Nate that there is a connection between places of rest and places of certainty because certainty would require a certain amount of stability.

621
00:53:46,660 --> 00:53:50,320
 Otherwise, that certainty is pretty false, right?

622
00:53:50,480 --> 00:53:57,520
 You need to have that, that's that stable ground from which to assert one's certainty.

623
00:53:57,820 --> 00:54:08,060
 So, yeah, I, I would say, I, I mean, again, I've, I've always, for whatever reason, I don't have the best ability to articulate, but I always think of this in terms of, of a cancer.

624
00:54:08,060 --> 00:54:10,460
 That there is still movement there.

625
00:54:10,540 --> 00:54:23,660
 It is still this, um, it is still a kind of change, but, um, and it, and, you know, it looks like a place, it looks like it's just the repetition of the same and there's some kind of stability and staticness there.

626
00:54:23,740 --> 00:54:28,820
 But only because there is this relentless reproduction machine going on.

627
00:54:29,180 --> 00:54:36,140
 And this is why Derrida is so attractive to me, attractive to me too, because there are virtually no resting places in, in his writing.

628
00:54:36,240 --> 00:54:39,860
 I mean, like, there's the critique of his, like, relativism, right?

629
00:54:39,960 --> 00:54:44,080
 The kind of, like, lazy, sloppy, like, anything goes in Derrida.

630
00:54:44,380 --> 00:54:45,100
 It's not that.

631
00:54:45,180 --> 00:54:45,960
 It's just suspicion.

632
00:54:46,420 --> 00:54:48,220
 It's self-consciousness is what that is.

633
00:54:48,260 --> 00:54:49,960
 Like, what, why is that a bad thing?

634
00:54:50,520 --> 00:54:53,640
 It has nothing to do with moral or conceptual relativism.

635
00:54:53,940 --> 00:54:57,900
 It's about rigorous scrutiny of your own movement of thinking, you know?

636
00:54:57,960 --> 00:54:58,200
 Right.

637
00:54:59,780 --> 00:55:12,880
 Well, and this is where, I mean, so for instance, I just, I'm squeamish around terms like rest and movement just because they're so, like, it just, it reminds me so much of years ago.

638
00:55:12,880 --> 00:55:24,640
 I mean, when, and I think a lot of people still think this, that the target of sort of postmodern thinking was Descartes and the cogito, right?

639
00:55:24,740 --> 00:55:26,160
 Like, I think.

640
00:55:26,460 --> 00:55:35,260
 And I just remember learning years ago, like, that's not, the cogito as a place of rest, the I thing, that's not troubling, right?

641
00:55:35,340 --> 00:55:40,680
 Like, that's, you know, it lives in its own little quasi-solipsistic universe.

642
00:55:41,360 --> 00:55:50,160
 I mean, the danger is the appropriation machine, which is, you know, there's a way in which, and I just always associated this with Hegel, right?

643
00:55:50,220 --> 00:56:04,000
 Hegel was, to me, Hegel was the real danger from Enlightenment thinking, not Descartes, insofar as what Hegel often, and by the way, I'm getting this from Adorno's, the negative, the dialectic of Enlightenment, right?

644
00:56:04,000 --> 00:56:09,840
 Like, the Odysseus stuff, where, like, the figure for Enlightenment should be Odysseus.

645
00:56:10,180 --> 00:56:30,700
 He's the guy who travels around all the foreign lands and kills, you know, like, appropriates the other into a version of the same, like, you know, putting a McDonald's in Red Square and on the moon and, you know, in other words, producing everything of a version of self, right, in that way, as at that form of appropriation.

646
00:56:30,700 --> 00:56:34,180
 So that that, so it was never an issue of stability versus movement.

647
00:56:34,340 --> 00:56:56,060
 It was always an issue of a movement that simply appropriates or projects itself versus a movement that expropriates, you know, that those differences, to me, were the key differences, you know, so, but in terms of how we're thinking of appropriation here, it's not the McDonald's at Red Square, you know.

648
00:56:56,060 --> 00:57:14,640
 It is not simply, I put a version of myself, the self-aliening move of otherness is not just, I make everything into a version of me, it is everything, you know, it's the self-other, mutually, self-transformative function.

649
00:57:16,980 --> 00:57:24,320
 Yeah, every appropriation is an expropriation, at least in the way we've been reading this version of Hegel, yeah.

650
00:57:24,720 --> 00:57:32,260
 So, it's the lack of comfort there that's appealing, right, like, you're not simply appropriating your environment or the other.

651
00:57:32,760 --> 00:57:38,660
 They're just as much affecting you, and there's no, there's no simple difference between the two.

652
00:57:38,760 --> 00:57:45,120
 There's no subject-object divide, whereas for Descartes, you know, there obviously was kind of a clean, a clean cut for him.

653
00:57:45,540 --> 00:57:58,320
 In Hegel, it's, it becomes indistinguishable to the point of, you could say paralysis in certain cases, but if you reach absolute spirit, it becomes freeing, or liberating in some way, you know.

654
00:57:58,960 --> 00:58:20,480
 But I still think you can make distinctions between different styles of appropriation there, where, like, some kinds of appropriation are more inclined to generate difference, and other kinds are less inclined, you know, like, I mean, you know, when I eat, I'm pretty much appropriating it to make myself, yes, of course, there is a change in my body.

655
00:58:20,480 --> 00:58:22,200
 You are what you eat, John, you are what you eat.

656
00:58:22,420 --> 00:58:32,420
 Right, but that's one, I mean, that's why eating is, to me, eating is an interesting, you know, circumstance to think about appropriation, right, and, and, because it is.

657
00:58:32,540 --> 00:58:37,860
 It's like, I'm taking in the other in an incredibly literal way, and what does that do?

658
00:58:37,960 --> 00:58:40,500
 Well, it does different kinds of things, right?

659
00:58:40,560 --> 00:58:49,120
 I mean, it's not simply, even if we just confine ourselves to that domain of eating, some things make you sick, some things, one pill makes you sick, sorry.

660
00:58:50,520 --> 00:59:03,800
 But, you know, there are different types of appropriation, or different ways that different foods, and different, so you have different kinds of appropriation, some of which are more transformative than others, and some of which are more simply self-replicative.

661
00:59:03,800 --> 00:59:23,200
 This is what is really interesting to me about disgust in the sort of gustatory register, is, you know, like, our tastes change, and, you know, what we find disgusting, and what, like, we literally want to throw up, or, like, gag at the thought of, changes based on our sort of encounters with, with difference.

662
00:59:23,200 --> 00:59:29,760
 And the thing that would, in one context, at one point in my life, make me want to throw up, becomes just a delight in another.

663
00:59:29,760 --> 00:59:30,520
 Your favorite suit.

664
00:59:31,040 --> 00:59:53,840
 Yeah, exactly, and, you know, I mean, this is a case where, I mean, I don't even think eating is a simple appropriation of the other, that it reorients you to, you know, a whole lot of things, and I, like, you know, in my own, like, development is the wrong word, but the sort of, like, my own cultivation of getting used to different kinds of foods.

665
00:59:53,840 --> 01:00:21,500
 It's just, like, you get, you get the hang of a handful of things, and now suddenly a whole array of things come into, like, become possible to experience and engage, and the sort of, the universal, you know, throw up reaction becomes, isn't replaced by some universal enjoyment action, but becomes replaced with this whole heterogeneous field of different kinds of experiences and orientations to things.

666
01:00:21,840 --> 01:00:34,420
 And that, you know, that, like, to me, that, there, there's, I feel like I'm, well, okay, that food is all shit now, so, I, I was gonna say that I'm far more expropriated than I, than it is appropriated, but.

667
01:00:35,680 --> 01:00:36,520
 Right, right, right.

668
01:00:36,520 --> 01:00:37,160
 I'm kind of expropriated, too.

669
01:00:37,160 --> 01:00:40,520
 Well, it's, it's transformative, you can certainly say that, I mean.

670
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:40,720
 Yeah.

671
01:00:41,100 --> 01:00:41,380
 Right.

672
01:00:41,840 --> 01:01:06,360
 But, again, that kind of points to the complexity of the for itself in Hegel, like, where, so, where something was, where something was previously disgusting or made you feel alienated or, like, kind of was scary to you, you can then, at a certain point, you know, revert or transform that thing into a positive experience.

673
01:01:06,360 --> 01:01:15,000
 So, like, it's, it's the same as Foucault's, like, you end up fetishizing the oppressor, basically, or, like, the thing, the thing that really scares you, you end up wanting.

674
01:01:15,780 --> 01:01:19,780
 Um, and it becomes part of that movement of spirit in, in Hegel's terms.

675
01:01:19,860 --> 01:01:24,040
 Like, I think of it with, um, with, like, really dissonant music.

676
01:01:24,420 --> 01:01:27,680
 Like, if you showed that to a baby, it's gonna cry.

677
01:01:28,100 --> 01:01:35,520
 Um, but you show it to a grad student, and he's gonna be like, ooh, this is really cool, and it's making, you know, my skin tingle, and it's, you know what I mean?

678
01:01:35,560 --> 01:01:51,140
 So, like, there's levels of that appropriative function, and it, again, you don't have to think of it, like, as totalizing in this, like, weird, uh, fascistic way, but, again, it's, like, the, the liberatory potential, uh, is, is obscured there.

679
01:01:51,380 --> 01:02:02,080
 Whereas, for, for a lot of thinkers, like, that's what they lean into, it's, like, the, the proliferation of desire, whereas, for someone like Hegel, it's, like, we should still be suspicious of that, you know?

680
01:02:02,140 --> 01:02:02,840
 Yeah, yeah.

681
01:02:03,360 --> 01:02:04,040
 I don't know.

682
01:02:04,960 --> 01:02:05,320
 Um.

683
01:02:05,780 --> 01:02:06,320
 Yeah, I mean.

684
01:02:06,360 --> 01:02:16,140
 Well, I don't know how much this is a response, but, like, I, I was really moved by Hume's sensibility of taste, like, I don't know, 10, 20 years ago.

685
01:02:16,140 --> 01:02:33,440
 Like, just, like, I, you know, I first came across it when I was taking an undergrad philosophy of art course, and, you know, just, like, the monotonous repetition of text, that thought that they had, sort of, like, discovered the right metric for determining good art from bad art was just, like, for me, exhausting.

686
01:02:33,440 --> 01:02:57,100
 And then, coming across Hume was, like, no, there are, like, bodies cultivate different orientations to, um, to, to food or, or, or, or whatever else it is, and they're not predetermined that, you know, these sorts of, sorts of things are played out in repetitions of, um, of exposure.

687
01:02:57,720 --> 01:03:02,920
 And, um, and so I was really excited to teach that to my students a year or two ago.

688
01:03:03,420 --> 01:03:25,280
 And my students reacted, like, really violently against it because, like, it was really scary for them to, to think that they're at a bodily level and at a psychological level that, that, um, uh, the stuff that they found repulsive or disgusting could, they could acquire a taste for it.

689
01:03:25,280 --> 01:03:28,700
 And that was, in some ways, a major threat to them.

690
01:03:29,140 --> 01:03:42,120
 And I think that you're totally right that then, that the other becomes fetishized insofar as it becomes, like, a life, like, the other becomes a life-sustaining thing for me because I'm able to demarcate myself against it and it's got to stay away.

691
01:03:42,120 --> 01:03:57,940
 But that, for me, that, like, the, the, the, you know, um, the fear of appropriation is very much so akin to a fear of, of, of, of, yeah, of self-transformation.

692
01:03:58,820 --> 01:04:01,720
 Like, I'm going to become it or it's going to become me.

693
01:04:01,880 --> 01:04:13,340
 Well, I, I remember, I mean, this is anecdotal, so irrelevant, but I mean, I, I remember, like, six years ago, I just kind of stopped liking the taste of beer.

694
01:04:14,120 --> 01:04:30,380
 And, and, and I, I remember when it happened, I mean, it was over the course of, like, a semester and I was just, like, you know, I, I kind of fought through it a few times at the speakeasy and whatever, because, and, and then there was a point where I was just, like, I just don't like drinking beer anymore.

695
01:04:30,380 --> 01:04:39,420
 And, like, that's such a central part of who I, how I think of who I am or, or was at the time that it was really kind of traumatic, right?

696
01:04:39,420 --> 01:04:43,940
 Like, who am I going to be if I don't like the taste of beer?

697
01:04:44,020 --> 01:04:49,460
 I mean, fortunately, I had scotch as a sort of side replacement, but, like, I don't even want to have a beer anymore.

698
01:04:49,460 --> 01:04:50,900
 And it's still true today.

699
01:04:51,160 --> 01:04:55,840
 Like, I just don't like, and it's not, I didn't have, like, a bad experience or anything like that.

700
01:04:55,920 --> 01:04:57,760
 And everything was going along just fine.

701
01:04:57,760 --> 01:05:02,780
 And then just a few times I was, like, eh, maybe I had a bad bottle, maybe I had whatever.

702
01:05:02,960 --> 01:05:05,120
 And then it was, like, I just don't like this stuff.

703
01:05:05,580 --> 01:05:10,000
 And it was, it was very hard to be, like, okay, I'm not, I'm just not a beer drinker anymore.

704
01:05:10,140 --> 01:05:12,260
 It's that identification move again.

705
01:05:12,940 --> 01:05:13,140
 Yeah.

706
01:05:13,280 --> 01:05:21,360
 This also, this sounds like it's also sort of been a part of this whole experiment of, like, what does the subtraction of alcohol do in my life?

707
01:05:21,360 --> 01:05:39,060
 Because, I mean, like, you know, the easy, like, the quick way of reading that is to say either you have, you know, your gustatory sensibilities have contracted and you've lost the capacity to appreciate something that's, you know, in and of itself good.

708
01:05:39,060 --> 01:05:45,580
 Or you've advanced beyond the vulgar taste of beer and you've gone into something more reified and you've cultivated.

709
01:05:46,040 --> 01:05:46,900
 Yeah, yeah, exactly.

710
01:05:47,020 --> 01:05:47,740
 Whatever it is.

711
01:05:48,460 --> 01:05:59,780
 But, you know, if you just accept, like, you know, the, the, the, the complex that is, you know, your ton and mouth in beer, like, that's not the, the whole story of liking beer.

712
01:05:59,880 --> 01:06:08,500
 That is connected to a whole lot of other things and it just opens up, it closes down some ways of living and it opens up other ones.

713
01:06:08,680 --> 01:06:14,440
 And that just becomes a far more interesting way of, of, of imagining that relationship to another.

714
01:06:14,920 --> 01:06:15,360
 This thing.

715
01:06:15,540 --> 01:06:16,440
 I mean, that's, yeah.

716
01:06:16,920 --> 01:06:23,340
 Like I told you, I told you guys when my TV blew up a few weeks ago, you know, and, and I just decided not to replace it.

717
01:06:23,340 --> 01:06:27,880
 And I always have the TV on, I very rarely watch it, but it's on a lot, especially with basketball.

718
01:06:28,120 --> 01:06:29,420
 And I was absolutely certain.

719
01:06:29,460 --> 01:06:36,040
 I'm like, well, I'm going to try this experiment because life presented me with this and I'm going to be a no TV person for a little while.

720
01:06:36,060 --> 01:06:40,100
 But I guarantee you I'll have the TV back before the NBA, you know, kicks off.

721
01:06:40,540 --> 01:06:43,500
 Two weeks into the NBA, I still don't have a TV, right?

722
01:06:43,560 --> 01:06:45,940
 Like, I mean, I've just, I'm, I'm just riding this.

723
01:06:45,940 --> 01:06:49,400
 And it was one of those situations that, okay, life presented me with this thing.

724
01:06:49,540 --> 01:06:50,900
 It was difficult at first.

725
01:06:50,980 --> 01:07:01,900
 I mean, I told you guys, like, I found myself reaching for the remote constantly, but now it's like, okay, my evenings are completely different because I'm not located with, you know, the TV on and the back on.

726
01:07:01,980 --> 01:07:05,480
 And when I, like, when I was texting you guys last night, like, I have to go find the game.

727
01:07:05,580 --> 01:07:08,300
 I can't just, the game doesn't just come on for me.

728
01:07:08,660 --> 01:07:10,780
 I have to make a very specific effort.

729
01:07:10,780 --> 01:07:13,920
 So the game that you guys were watching, I couldn't get.

730
01:07:14,080 --> 01:07:15,680
 So I went to the other game, you know.

731
01:07:17,040 --> 01:07:18,200
 So it's done.

732
01:07:18,760 --> 01:07:20,400
 It produces different, it's a transformation.

733
01:07:20,980 --> 01:07:24,880
 I mean, habits are so complex and difficult to break.

734
01:07:25,000 --> 01:07:27,020
 Like, you can't, you have to re-articulate them.

735
01:07:27,160 --> 01:07:29,680
 You can't simply, like, abandon a habit, right?

736
01:07:29,740 --> 01:07:36,760
 And so when you disidentify with a habit that's so crucial to your sense of self, I mean, that's disorienting.

737
01:07:36,860 --> 01:07:43,180
 Like, I always come back, I always come back to music because it's something I consume compulsively and just way too much.

738
01:07:43,260 --> 01:07:54,720
 And it's like, when I no longer, like, there's music where, from a few years ago, used to bring me so much pleasure and certain artists that I just consumed all goddamn day.

739
01:07:54,900 --> 01:08:02,000
 And now, after certain changes in my life and those memories of that music are associated with things, right?

740
01:08:02,080 --> 01:08:04,620
 Like, I no longer, it's now, like, painful.

741
01:08:05,100 --> 01:08:08,760
 So, like, music that I used to love is now I have to, like, reject in some way.

742
01:08:08,840 --> 01:08:14,240
 And it's like, it's just such a strange experience where you have to, like, no longer, yeah, consume that.

743
01:08:14,800 --> 01:08:31,740
 But I think that to be generous towards the, what I earlier referred to as the kind of dumb liberal appropriations of the broad or whatever else, I think a lot of what they're, what's feeding that is an interest in people just getting okay with their idiosyncratic desires.

744
01:08:32,000 --> 01:08:44,440
 And that because so much of the, I mean, this certainly animates Butler for, without question, but others as well, I do think that there is a sense of, like, look, you can just like the things that you like.

745
01:08:44,800 --> 01:08:57,320
 And you don't, it doesn't really matter whether that's, you know, heteronormative or whatever, you know, like, just be okay with your desires and with their transformations and mutations and whatever else.

746
01:08:57,380 --> 01:09:13,140
 I mean, I do think that that, for instance, Anti-Oedipus, I mean, that's certainly an animating sensibility behind that is, like, just get okay with your desire or with desire and how it operates sort of through you in that regard.

